In 2022, Kazakhstan's agricultural sector demonstrated notable growth in
both animal husbandry and crop production, reflecting positive dynamics
in comparison with the previous year. The French total production volume
in the livestock sector reached 25 127.3 million tenge, which is 103.6\%
of the level of 2021, which indicates the stability and steady growth of
this sector. The volume of production in crop production amounted to 12
623.7 million tenge, which is 110.6\% more than in the previous year,
which indicates a rapid increase in agricultural production. If we
consider the specific results of animal husbandry, the country produced
12 463.3 tons of meat (in live weight), which is 104.3\% of the previous
year' s level. Milk production also increased to 40 727.6
tons (105.2\%), and egg production reached 2 578.200, which is 102.5\%
more than in the previous year. These figures confirm not only the high
growth rates of the agricultural sector, but also its significant
contribution to ensuring food security. In this regard, it is important
to continue analyzing the main trends in agricultural production in
Kazakhstan, as this region plays an important role in the development of
agricultural production and the stability of the
country' s economy.

In January-July 2025, Kazakhstan' s livestock industry
demonstrated positive dynamics: the gross physical output index was
103.2\% compared to the same period last year, the volume of livestock
and poultry slaughter in live weight increased by 1.4\%, milk production
increased by 7\%, and the production of eggs increased by 0.9\%. At the
same time, the structure of the livestock population was distributed as
follows: cattle are concentrated mainly in the population (46.3\%) and
farms (43.7\%), sheep --- in farms (52.4\%) and in the population
(41\%), goats mainly in the population (65\%), while pig and poultry
farming They are mostly concentrated in agricultural enterprises (50.5\%
and 82.8\%, respectively). Average productivity indicators show mixed
trends: milk yield per cow decreased by 0.6\%, and egg yield per laying
hen increased by 0.8\%. These results confirm the sustainable
development of the industry while maintaining its key role in ensuring
the country' s food security (Table 3).

